File: gdocs.info,  Node: OAuth flow,  Next: Token management,  Up: Authentication (1)

5.1 OAuth flow
==============

The OAuth 2.0 flow works as follows:

  1. The user runs ‘M-x gdocs-authenticate’.
  2. A temporary local HTTP server starts on a random high port to
     receive the authorization callback.
  3. The user's default browser opens to Google's OAuth consent screen.
  4. After the user grants consent, Google redirects to the local server
     with an authorization code.
  5. The package exchanges the code for access and refresh tokens.
  6. Tokens are stored in ‘gdocs-token-directory’ with 600 permissions.

   The package requests two OAuth scopes:

   • ‘https://www.googleapis.com/auth/documents’ for reading and writing
     Google Docs.
   • ‘https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive’ for listing, browsing, and
     creating files in Google Drive.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Token management,  Next: Multi-account support,  Prev: OAuth flow,  Up: Authentication (1)

5.2 Token management
====================

Access tokens are refreshed automatically before each API call when they
are expired or within 60 seconds of expiry.  The refresh uses the stored
refresh token and happens asynchronously, so Emacs is never blocked.
Each token file also stores the ‘client_id’ and ‘client_secret’ so that
token refreshes work without re-reading ‘gdocs-accounts’.

   If no token file exists for an account (e.g., after running
‘gdocs-logout’), the next API operation triggers a fresh OAuth flow.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Multi-account support,  Prev: Token management,  Up: Authentication (1)

5.3 Multi-account support
=========================

Each entry in ‘gdocs-accounts’ is an independent account with its own
OAuth credentials and token file.  Linked org files remember which
account they are associated with via the ‘GDOCS_ACCOUNT’ property in the
file-level property drawer (*note Metadata storage::).  When you open a
linked file, the stored account is used automatically.

   You would configure custom OAuth credentials per account if you want
to avoid shared rate limits or if your organization requires its own
OAuth application.


