8.1 Metadata storage
====================

Each linked org file stores sync metadata in a file-level property
drawer at the top of the file:

     :PROPERTIES:
     :GDOCS_DOCUMENT_ID: 1BxiMVs0XRA5nFMdKvBdBZjgmUUqptlbs74OgVE2upms
     :GDOCS_ACCOUNT: personal
     :GDOCS_REVISION_ID: ALm37BVT...
     :GDOCS_LAST_SYNC: 2024-01-15T10:30:00+0000
     :END:

   The property drawer is the standard org-mode mechanism for
document-level metadata.  All four properties are persisted to the file,
so revision tracking and last-sync timestamps survive across Emacs
sessions.  The drawer is read via ‘org-entry-get’ and written via
‘org-entry-put’, using standard org APIs rather than the Emacs
file-local variable machinery.

   Directories linked to Google Drive folders (*note Directory
linking::) store their association in ‘.dir-locals.el’ rather than
per-file:

     ((org-mode . ((gdocs-folder-id . "1A2B3C4D5E6F...")
                   (gdocs-account . "personal"))))

   This means every org file in the directory inherits the folder and
account settings.  ‘gdocs-create’ uses these values to place new
documents in the correct Drive folder.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Shadow copy,  Next: Push serialization,  Prev: Metadata storage,  Up: Sync engine

8.2 Shadow copy
===============

The sync engine maintains a buffer-local _shadow IR_: the intermediate
representation of the last-synced state.  This shadow enables
incremental diffs on push and conflict detection on pull.

   On the first open of a linked file after an Emacs restart, the shadow
is ‘nil’.  The next push fetches the remote document and diffs against
it (rather than against the missing shadow), so incremental diffing
still works and comment anchors are preserved.  If
‘gdocs-auto-pull-on-open’ is non-nil, the pull establishes the shadow
baseline automatically so that subsequent pushes diff against the
known-good shadow.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Push serialization,  Next: Post-push list nesting fixup,  Prev: Shadow copy,  Up: Sync engine

8.3 Push serialization
======================

Pushes are serialized to prevent race conditions.  If a push is already
in flight when another is triggered (e.g., by a rapid save), the second
push is queued and executes automatically when the first completes.
This ensures that the shadow copy is always consistent with what was
last sent to the API.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Post-push list nesting fixup,  Prev: Push serialization,  Up: Sync engine

8.4 Post-push list nesting fixup
================================

The diff engine emits ‘createParagraphBullets’ requests for new list
items and for modifications that change the list type or nesting level.
These per-paragraph requests always produce flat (level-0) lists.  The
full conversion path has a separate mechanism
(‘gdocs-convert--fixup-list-nesting’) that groups bullets and inserts
leading tabs so that the API infers correct nesting levels, but the diff
path cannot use that mechanism because it interleaves modifications with
insertions at varying document positions.

   When a content modification does not change the list structure (same
type and level), the diff engine suppresses the ‘createParagraphBullets’
request entirely.  The trailing newline is preserved during paragraph
modifications, which keeps the paragraph in its existing Google Docs
list object.  Re-emitting a bullet request with a fixed preset would
overwrite the alternated preset assigned during document creation and
cause Google Docs to merge separate numbered lists into one continuous
sequence.

   To restore correct nesting, the sync engine runs a second
‘batchUpdate’ pass after the main push succeeds, but only when the local
IR contains nested list items (level > 0).  The fixup proceeds as
follows:

  1. Fetch the just-pushed document to obtain current paragraph ranges.

  2. Align local and remote IR elements by plain-text content using the
     same LCS approach as the diff engine, so that each local element
     (which carries the correct ‘:level’ from the org source) is paired
     with its remote counterpart (which carries ‘:doc-start’ /
     ‘:doc-end’ positions).

  3. Build element-range plists that merge local list info with remote
     document positions.  The local element's ‘:list’ always takes
     precedence, even when nil — this ensures that headings erroneously
     bulleted by the API are correctly treated as non-list elements by
     the guard logic in step 6.

  4. Identify contiguous list groups that contain at least one element
     at level > 0.

  5. For each such group, emit four kinds of requests in order:
        • ‘deleteParagraphBullets’ to remove the flat bullets for the
          group range.
        • ‘updateParagraphStyle’ to reset ‘indentStart’ and
          ‘indentFirstLine’ to zero, so only leading tabs signal nesting
          depth.
        • ‘insertText’ to insert _N_ tab characters at each nested
          paragraph's ‘startIndex’ (where _N_ is the nesting level).
          Insertions are sorted by descending index to maintain correct
          positions.
        • A per-group ‘createParagraphBullets’ request.  The API counts
          the leading tabs, assigns the correct nesting levels, and
          removes the tabs afterward.

  6. Emit defensive ‘deleteParagraphBullets’ requests for non-list
     paragraphs adjacent to the list groups.  The Google Docs API can
     extend bullet formatting to heading paragraphs near
     ‘createParagraphBullets’ ranges, so these guards prevent headings
     from being accidentally turned into bullet points.

   The fixup keeps the push lock held until completion, so any queued
push waits until nesting is fully resolved before proceeding (*note Push
serialization::).  If the local IR has no nested list items, the fixup
is skipped entirely and the push completes in a single round trip.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Diff engine,  Next: Conflict resolution,  Prev: Sync engine,  Up: Top

9 Diff engine
*************

The incremental diff engine computes the minimal set of Google Docs API
‘batchUpdate’ requests to transform the remote document from its
last-known state to the current org state.

* Menu:

* Approach::
* Word-level diff::
* Text-style reset::
* Comment-aware push::


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Approach,  Next: Word-level diff,  Up: Diff engine

9.1 Approach
============

  1. Produce content-based keys for each element in the old and new IRs.
     Keys capture type, style, text content, and formatting, so elements
     with identical content produce identical keys.

  2. Run a longest-common-subsequence (LCS) algorithm on the key lists
     to identify which elements are kept, deleted, inserted, or
     modified.  Adjacent delete+insert pairs of the same type are
     collapsed into modify operations.

  3. Compute the UTF-16 document position of each old element.  When the
     old IR was produced from Google Docs JSON, elements carry
     ‘:doc-start’ / ‘:doc-end’ properties with the authoritative byte
     offsets reported by the API; the engine uses those directly.  For
     IR produced from org-mode (which lacks document positions), it
     falls back to computing positions from element text lengths.
     Insertion points for new elements are determined by the end
     position of the nearest preceding kept or modified element;
     modified elements are valid anchors because they still occupy a
     known position in the old document.

  4. Map operations to API requests:
        • *Insert*: ‘InsertText’, ‘InsertTable’,
          ‘CreateParagraphBullets’, etc.
        • *Delete*: ‘DeleteContentRange’.
        • *Modify*: for style-only changes, ‘UpdateParagraphStyle’; for
          formatting-only changes, ‘UpdateTextStyle’; for content
          changes, word-level surgical diff (*note Word-level diff::).

  5. Order requests correctly: deletions in reverse index order (highest
     first), then insertions in forward order.  This is necessary
     because the Google Docs API processes requests sequentially and
     earlier operations shift later indices.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Word-level diff,  Next: Text-style reset,  Prev: Approach,  Up: Diff engine

9.2 Word-level diff
===================

When a paragraph's text content changes, the diff engine performs a
word-level diff rather than deleting all text and re-inserting it.  This
is critical for preserving Google Docs comments: comments are anchored
to specific text ranges via opaque internal identifiers that cannot be
recreated through any API.  A full delete+re-insert destroys all comment
anchors, even on text that did not change.

   The word-level algorithm works as follows:

  1. Tokenize the old and new paragraph text into alternating word
     tokens (contiguous non-whitespace) and whitespace tokens
     (contiguous spaces or tabs).  This preserves exact spacing.

  2. Run the LCS algorithm on the token strings to identify which tokens
     are kept, deleted, or inserted.

  3. Collapse adjacent same-operation tokens into contiguous ranges.

  4. Generate ‘DeleteContentRange’ requests for deleted ranges (sorted
     highest to lowest by document index) and ‘InsertText’ requests for
     inserted text at the correct post-deletion positions.

  5. Apply paragraph style, text formatting, and list property requests
     for the full new paragraph extent (same as before).

   Token offsets are computed in UTF-16 code units using
‘gdocs-convert--string-to-utf16-length’ to handle non-BMP characters
(such as emoji) that require surrogate pairs.  Even a fully rewritten
paragraph produces correct operations.  The word-level approach is used
whenever the list structure is unchanged (same type and level, or both
non-list); modifications that change the list type or nesting level fall
back to a bulk replacement to handle the tab prefix and bullet preset
changes that list transitions require.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Text-style reset,  Next: Comment-aware push,  Prev: Word-level diff,  Up: Diff engine

9.3 Text-style reset
====================

When new text is inserted into a Google Doc--whether by the full
conversion path or by the incremental diff engine--it inherits the
formatting of adjacent text.  This means that inserting a plain
paragraph next to a bold one would produce bold text unless the
formatting is explicitly cleared.

   To prevent inherited formatting from bleeding into new content, every
text insertion is followed by an ‘updateTextStyle’ request that resets
all character-level formatting across the inserted range.  The reset
clears bold, italic, underline, strikethrough, ‘weightedFontFamily’,
‘baselineOffset’, ‘foregroundColor’, and ‘backgroundColor’ by listing
them in the API's ‘fields’ mask with only default values in the
‘textStyle’ body.  Fields present in the mask but absent from the body
are reset to their defaults by the Google Docs API.  After the reset,
per-run style requests re-apply only the formatting that the org source
actually specifies.  This two-step approach (reset then re-apply)
ensures that every text run matches the org source exactly, regardless
of surrounding context.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Comment-aware push,  Prev: Text-style reset,  Up: Diff engine

9.4 Comment-aware push
======================

When ‘gdocs-preserve-comments’ is non-nil (*note Sync behavior::), the
push flow adds a comment protection step between computing the diff and
sending the batch update.  The extended flow is:

  1. Fetch the remote document (as before).
  2. Fetch all comments on the document via the Drive Comments API
     (‘gdocs-api-list-comments’).  Deleted and resolved comments are
     excluded from the mapping, so they never trigger prompts.
  3. Compute the diff operations (‘gdocs-diff-compute-operations’).
  4. For each destructive operation (element deletion or cross-type
     modification), check whether the target element has comments
     anchored to it.  A comment is considered "on" an element if the
     comment's ‘quotedFileContent.value’ appears as a substring of the
     element's plain text.
  5. Prompt the user for each at-risk operation via a single-key prompt
     showing the element text, comment author, and comment content.  The
     prompt offers four actions:
        • ‘[s]kip’ - keep the element in the remote document, preserving
          the comment.
        • ‘[d]elete’ - proceed with the deletion, destroying the
          comment.
        • ‘[o]pen’ - open the comment in the browser using the Google
          Docs comment URL
          (‘https://docs.google.com/document/d/DOC-ID/edit?disco=COMMENT-ID’),
          then re-prompt for the same element so you can inspect the
          comment in context before deciding.
        • ‘[r]esolve & delete’ - resolve the comment via the Drive
          Comments API (‘gdocs-api-resolve-comment’) before proceeding
          with the deletion.  This marks the discussion as resolved
          while still removing the element from the document.
     Uppercase variants (‘S’, ‘D’, ‘R’) apply the chosen action to all
     remaining conflicts, so you do not have to answer individually for
     every at-risk element.
  6. Remove declined (skipped) operations from the diff operation list.
  7. Generate API requests from the filtered operations
     (‘gdocs-diff-generate-from-ops’).
  8. Send the batch update.
  9. Reconstruct the shadow IR to account for declined deletions: the
     shadow starts with the local IR, and declined elements (from the
     remote IR) are re-inserted at the correct positions.

   Declined elements remain in the remote document.  On the next push,
the diff will again classify them as deletions and prompt again.

   Comments without quoted text (document-level comments) are never
considered at risk.  Resolved comments are still prompted, since they
represent valuable discussion history.


